{
  "What is environmental justice?": "",
  "The legal system used to prosecute environmental crimes": "",
  "Protection of wilderness areas from industrial development": "",
  "Fair treatment and meaningful involvement of all people regardless of race, color, income, or national origin in environmental matters": "",
  "Equal funding for all national parks regardless of location": "",
  "Environmental justice is the principle that all people deserve fair treatment and meaningful involvement in environmental decision-making, regardless of their race, income, or national origin.": "",
  "Studies have shown that hazardous waste facilities are disproportionately located in which types of communities?": "",
  "Communities near major universities": "",
  "Communities are chosen equally at random": "",
  "Suburban communities with high property values": "",
  "Minority and low-income communities": "",
  "Research has consistently documented that hazardous waste facilities, landfills, and polluting industries are disproportionately sited in minority and low-income communities, a pattern known as environmental racism.": "",
  "Why was the 1982 Warren County, North Carolina protest a landmark event?": "",
  "It was the first successful lawsuit under the Clean Water Act": "",
  "It was the first major environmental justice protest, opposing a PCB landfill in a predominantly Black community, and sparked the EJ movement": "",
  "It was the first protest against nuclear power in the United States": "",
  "It resulted in the creation of the EPA": "",
  "The 1982 Warren County protests against the siting of a PCB landfill in a predominantly African American community is widely regarded as the birth of the environmental justice movement in the United States.": "",
  "What caused the Flint, Michigan water crisis?": "",
  "Switching water sources to save money, which corroded pipes and leached lead into drinking water, primarily affecting Black residents": "",
  "An industrial chemical spill from a nearby factory": "",
  "Excessive agricultural runoff contaminating the city's reservoir": "",
  "A natural drought that contaminated the local aquifer": "",
  "The Flint water crisis resulted from a cost-saving decision to switch the city's water source without proper treatment, causing corrosion that leached lead from aging pipes into drinking water in a predominantly Black community.": "",
  "What does Cancer Alley in Louisiana demonstrate about environmental justice?": "",
  "That industrial pollution affects all communities equally": "",
  "That concentrated petrochemical industries in a predominantly Black corridor lead to elevated cancer and respiratory disease rates": "",
  "That natural carcinogens in Louisiana soil cause higher cancer rates": "",
  "That cancer rates are uniform across all parishes in Louisiana": "",
  "Cancer Alley, an 85-mile stretch along the Mississippi River between Baton Rouge and New Orleans, demonstrates environmental racism through the concentration of petrochemical facilities in predominantly Black communities, resulting in elevated rates of cancer and respiratory illness.": "",
  "What did Executive Order 12898 (1994) require?": "",
  "Federal agencies to identify and address disproportionately high environmental and health effects on minority and low-income populations": "",
  "All states to create environmental justice offices": "",
  "Industries to relocate away from residential areas": "",
  "The closure of all hazardous waste facilities in minority communities": "",
  "Executive Order 12898, signed by President Clinton, directed every federal agency to make environmental justice part of its mission by identifying and addressing disproportionate environmental and health impacts on minority and low-income communities.": "",
  "What does the NIMBY ('Not In My Back Yard') phenomenon refer to?": "",
  "Communities that actively seek industrial development for economic growth": "",
  "A federal zoning regulation that prevents industrial siting near homes": "",
  "An environmental protection strategy that evenly distributes pollution sources": "",
  "The tendency of wealthier, politically powerful communities to successfully push unwanted facilities to less powerful communities": "",
  "NIMBY describes how wealthy, politically connected communities use their power and resources to oppose unwanted facilities, which then get sited in less powerful communities that lack the resources to resist.": "",
  "What are some environmental justice concerns facing Indigenous communities?": "",
  "Only concerns about preserving traditional languages": "",
  "Natural resource extraction on their lands, contaminated water, broken treaties, and loss of cultural resources": "",
  "Indigenous communities face no unique environmental challenges": "",
  "Only access to recreational facilities in national parks": "",
  "Indigenous communities face distinct environmental justice issues including resource extraction on their ancestral lands, contaminated water supplies, violations of treaty rights, and destruction of culturally significant natural resources.": "",
  "How does climate change relate to environmental justice?": "",
  "Climate impacts disproportionately affect low-income communities and communities of color through heat islands, flood zones, and less access to adaptation resources": "",
  "Only coastal communities are affected by climate-related environmental injustice": "",
  "Climate change affects all communities equally": "",
  "Climate change has no connection to social equity": "",
  "Climate change is an environmental justice issue because its impacts, such as extreme heat, flooding, and air quality degradation, fall disproportionately on low-income communities and communities of color that often have fewer resources to adapt.": "",
  "What does the Justice40 Initiative (2021) aim to accomplish?": "",
  "Reduce all pollution by 40% within ten years": "",
  "Fund 40 new environmental justice research centers": "",
  "Deliver 40% of benefits from federal climate and environment investments to disadvantaged communities": "",
  "Close 40% of polluting facilities in minority communities": "",
  "The Justice40 Initiative directs that at least 40% of the overall benefits from federal investments in clean energy, clean transit, and environmental remediation flow to disadvantaged communities that are overburdened by pollution.": "",
  "What are cumulative impacts in the context of environmental justice?": "",
  "The number of environmental regulations that apply to a specific industry": "",
  "The combined health effects of multiple environmental hazards in one community, including air, water, soil pollution, and social stressors": "",
  "The financial costs accumulated by environmental cleanup efforts": "",
  "The total amount of pollution produced by a single factory over its lifetime": "",
  "Cumulative impacts refer to the combined burden of multiple environmental hazards and social stressors experienced simultaneously by a community, which can compound health effects beyond what any single exposure would cause.": "",
  "What is environmental racism?": "",
  "The disproportionate siting of environmentally hazardous facilities and exposure to pollution in communities of color due to systemic racial discrimination": "",
  "Preferential treatment given to certain species in conservation programs": "",
  "Any form of racial discrimination that occurs outdoors": "",
  "Competition between nations for access to natural resources": "",
  "Environmental racism refers to the systemic pattern in which communities of color are disproportionately exposed to environmental hazards and excluded from environmental decision-making due to institutional and structural racial discrimination.": "",
  "What is environmental gentrification?": "",
  "Government-funded relocation programs for communities near polluted areas": "",
  "The process by which environmental cleanup or green amenities raise property values and displace the original community that suffered the pollution": "",
  "The renovation of old factories into environmentally friendly buildings": "",
  "The construction of luxury housing on former parkland": "",
  "Environmental gentrification occurs when environmental improvements, such as park creation or pollution cleanup, increase property values and living costs to the point where the original residents who endured years of environmental harm are displaced.": "",
  "What is community-based participatory research (CBPR)?": "",
  "Online forums where citizens can comment on proposed research projects": "",
  "An approach in which residents of affected communities partner with researchers in designing and conducting studies on environmental health threats": "",
  "Research conducted exclusively by government scientists in affected communities": "",
  "A type of survey distributed to community members about their environmental opinions": "",
  "Community-based participatory research empowers affected community residents as equal partners in the research process, ensuring that local knowledge informs study design and that results directly address community concerns.": "",
  "What is Title VI of the Civil Rights Act and how does it relate to environmental justice?": "",
  "It prohibits discrimination in federally funded programs, allowing EPA to investigate claims of environmental discrimination": "",
  "It creates mandatory environmental impact statements for all federal projects": "",
  "It mandates environmental education in public schools": "",
  "It requires equal distribution of environmental hazards across all zip codes": "",
  "Title VI of the Civil Rights Act prohibits discrimination on the basis of race, color, or national origin in programs receiving federal funding, which provides a legal basis for EPA to investigate claims that environmental permitting disproportionately harms minority communities.": "",
  "What is the concept of climate justice?": "",
  "A legal framework for prosecuting greenhouse gas emitters": "",
  "The recognition that developing nations disproportionately suffer climate impacts caused largely by developed nations' historical emissions": "",
  "A treaty requiring all nations to reduce emissions by the same percentage": "",
  "The equal distribution of renewable energy infrastructure across all nations": "",
  "Climate justice recognizes the inequity that nations and communities that contributed least to historical greenhouse gas emissions often suffer the most severe climate impacts while having the fewest resources to adapt.": "",
  "What is procedural justice in environmental decision-making?": "",
  "The legal procedures required to file an environmental lawsuit": "",
  "The fair and meaningful involvement of all affected people in environmental decisions that affect their lives": "",
  "The step-by-step process for writing environmental regulations": "",
  "The procedure for conducting environmental impact assessments": "",
  "Procedural justice in the environmental context means ensuring that all affected communities, especially marginalized ones, have genuine access to and meaningful participation in the decision-making processes that shape environmental outcomes.": "",
  "What is distributive justice in environmental policy?": "",
  "The allocation of federal environmental funds to each state equally": "",
  "The process of distributing environmental monitoring equipment to agencies": "",
  "The distribution of environmental research grants among universities": "",
  "The fair allocation of environmental benefits and burdens across all segments of society": "",
  "Distributive justice concerns the fair allocation of both environmental benefits (such as clean air, green spaces, and safe water) and burdens (such as pollution, waste facilities, and health risks) across all communities regardless of race or income.": "",
  "What is the concept of intersectionality in environmental justice?": "",
  "The intersection of highways and industrial zones that creates pollution hotspots": "",
  "The overlap between state and federal environmental regulations": "",
  "The idea that environmental injustice intersects with multiple forms of social inequality including race, income, gender, and immigration status": "",
  "The geographical point where two polluted rivers meet": "",
  "Intersectionality in environmental justice recognizes that environmental burdens are compounded by overlapping social inequalities, so a low-income immigrant woman of color, for example, may face layered vulnerabilities that amplify environmental health risks.": "",
  "What is the EJScreen tool?": "",
  "A type of air quality monitor installed in disadvantaged communities": "",
  "An EPA mapping and screening tool that combines environmental and demographic data to identify communities with potential environmental justice concerns": "",
  "A social media platform for environmental justice activists": "",
  "A filtration system designed to remove toxins from drinking water": "",
  "EJScreen is an EPA environmental justice mapping tool that integrates environmental indicators (like proximity to hazardous waste sites and air quality data) with demographic information to help identify areas with potential environmental justice concerns.": "",
  "A city plans to build a new waste incinerator. Community meetings are held during work hours on weekdays, materials are only available in English, and the proposed site is in a predominantly low-income Hispanic neighborhood while wealthier neighborhoods were never considered. Which aspects of environmental justice are being violated?": "",
  "Only distributive justice": "",
  "Only Title VI violations because English-only materials were provided": "",
  "Both procedural justice (meaningful participation is prevented) and distributive justice (burdens are inequitably placed)": "",
  "No environmental justice concerns exist because meetings were held": "",
  "This scenario violates both procedural justice (meetings scheduled during work hours, English-only materials) and distributive justice (unfairly burdening a low-income minority community), demonstrating how environmental injustice operates on multiple levels.": "",
  "A formerly polluted industrial site in a low-income neighborhood is cleaned up and converted into a large park with new trails and amenities. Over the next few years, housing costs in the area rise sharply, and many long-time residents who lived near the pollution for decades can no longer afford to stay. What concept does this situation illustrate?": "",
  "Successful environmental justice policy": "",
  "Environmental gentrification": "",
  "The NIMBY phenomenon": "",
  "The tragedy of the commons": "",
  "This is environmental gentrification: the community that endured years of pollution is displaced when the environmental improvement raises property values, meaning the very people who suffered the harm do not benefit from the cleanup.": "",
  "A community near multiple industrial facilities has elevated rates of asthma, lead poisoning, and certain cancers. Residents also face high unemployment, food insecurity, and limited healthcare access. An environmental health study that examines only the air pollution from one nearby factory would fail to capture which important concept?": "",
  "The NIMBY effect, particularly regarding fails based": "",
  "Cumulative impacts from multiple environmental and social stressors": "",
  "Point-source pollution in the context of this analysis": "",
  "The precautionary principle as determined by standard methodology": "",
  "Focusing on a single pollution source fails to account for cumulative impacts, which are the combined health effects of multiple environmental hazards plus social stressors like poverty and lack of healthcare that compound vulnerability.": "",
  "A Native American reservation has uranium mining waste left over from Cold War-era extraction. The community has higher cancer rates, contaminated groundwater, and no cleanup funding. The federal government argues the mining was conducted by private companies. This scenario demonstrates which environmental justice issues?": "",
  "Only occupational safety issues for former mine workers": "",
  "Environmental gentrification of reservation land": "",
