  "Only water quality concerns regulated by the Clean Water Act": "",
  "This scenario illustrates Indigenous environmental justice issues: resource extraction on Native lands led to lasting contamination, and government failure to ensure cleanup reflects the historical pattern of environmental burdens falling disproportionately on Indigenous communities.": "",
  "Researchers want to study high asthma rates in a low-income urban neighborhood. Instead of designing the study themselves and collecting data from the community, they partner with local residents who help design surveys, collect air quality samples, and interpret results. This approach exemplifies which research methodology?": "",
  "Environmental impact assessment": "",
  "Traditional epidemiological research": "",
  "Community-based participatory research (CBPR)": "",
  "Randomized controlled trial": "",
  "This is community-based participatory research, which treats community members as equal partners in the research process, ensuring studies are relevant to the community's actual concerns and that local knowledge strengthens the research design.": "",
  "A wealthy coastal suburb successfully blocks the construction of a waste treatment plant in its community. The plant is instead built next to a low-income minority community on the other side of the city that lacks the political connections and legal resources to oppose it. Which concept best explains this pattern?": "",
  "Climate justice and adaptation inequality": "",
  "Cumulative impacts from multiple stressors": "",
  "The NIMBY phenomenon and its relationship to environmental injustice": "",
  "NIMBY (Not In My Back Yard) becomes an environmental justice issue when communities with greater political and economic power successfully deflect unwanted facilities to less powerful communities, perpetuating the inequitable distribution of environmental burdens.": "",
